<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-11-03T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-11-03T12:00:00-05:00" n="188" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d188">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">701.0611/372: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in France (<persName type="from">Armour</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-11-03T17:00:00+00:00">November 3, 1930—5
                                        p.m.</date><lb/>[Received November 3—2:10 p.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>351. Please telegraph whether clerks French Embassy, Washington, are
                                immune from income tax as a matter of principle or only because <pb facs="0364" n="274" xml:id="pg_274"/> salaries less than amount
                                of personal exemption allowed all residents. American clerks here
                                subject to French income tax and case of National Exposition
                                hardship has arisen which renders advisable renewed effort to secure
                                exemption on their behalf provided reciprocity can be shown.</p>
                            <closer><signed><persName><hi rend="smallcaps">Armour</hi></persName></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>